<glossary>
<definition id="fs-id1167133780016">
<term>Cassegrain design</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167133780021">arrangement of an objective and eyepiece such that the light-gathering concave mirror has a hole in the middle, and light then is incident on an eyepiece lens</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1167133805304">
<term>compound microscope</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167133805309">microscope constructed from two convex lenses, the first serving as the eyepiece and the second serving as the objective lens</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1167133805314">
<term>eyepiece</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167132225517">lens or combination of lenses in an optical instrument nearest to the eye of the observer</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1167132225521">
<term>net magnification</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167132225526">(<m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>M</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">net</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math>) of the compound microscope is the product of the linear magnification of the objective and the angular magnification of the eyepiece</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1167132256840">
<term>Newtonian design</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167132256845">arrangement of an objective and eyepiece such that the focused light from the concave mirror was reflected to one side of the tube into an eyepiece</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1167132256852">
<term>objective</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1167132256857">lens nearest to the object being examined.</meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
